<h3>Zoological Type Notes --<b>M</b> </h3>

<hr>
<A name="Megaceryle" id="Megaceryle"></a>
Megaceryle <strong>Type</strong>
<ul>
<li>The type is given by Peters Checklist <b>5</b>:165 as<pre>
Type, by subsequent designation, <i>Alcedo guttata</i> Vigors = <i>Ceryle guttulata</i>
Stejneger (Sharpe, Monogr. Alced., 1871, p.viii.)</pre>
Which I interpret to mean that Sharpe designated the type as <i>Ceryle guttata</i> Vigors.</li>
<li>Peters lists "<i>Ceryle guttulata</i> Stejneger, Proc.U.S.Nat.Mus., <b>15</b>, 1892, p.294
in text (India and China). New name for <i>Alcedo guttata</i> Vigors, 1831, not <i>Alcedo guttata</i> 
Boddaert, 1783."<ul>
	<li>I expect Peters means <i>Alcedo guttatus</i> <a href="../bio/biov.html#Vigors" target="ref_fr">Vigors</a> 
	1831 <i><a href="../cit/jourp.html#PZS" target="ref_fr">PZS</a></i> Pt1 no.2 p.22 (APP:not <i>guttata</i>).</li>
	</ul></li>
<li>The Richmond Index lists the type as <i>Alcedo guttata</i>Boddaert = <i>Alcedo maxima</i>
Pallas. I expect the taxon here is:<ul>
	<li>Alcedo guttata <a href="../bio/biob.html#Boddaert" 
	target="ref_fr">Boddaert</a> 1783 <i><a 
	href="../cit/jourt.html#TablePlanchesEnlum." target="ref_fr">TablePlanchesEnlum.</a></i> 
	p.42</li>
	<li>The Richmond Index notes that the above taxon is <pre>
	Based on Daubenton, Pl. Enl. 679. "Martin-p&ecirc;cheur hup&eacute;
	du Cap de Bonne-Esperance." (Buffon, VII, p.188).</li>
</ul>

</ul>
2005.05.07

<hr>
<A name="M.m.mercedesfosterae" id="M.m.mercedesfosterae"></a>
Mionectes macconnelli mercedesfosterae <strong>Type</strong>
<ul>
<li>Mercedes Foster indicates <i>in litt.</i> 2004.12.03.<pre>
The type of M. m. mercedesfosterae was collected by Dickerman (#17102) and is
deposited in the AMNH (#816795).</pre></li>
</ul>
2004.12.04


<hr><A name="S.z.minorType" id="S.z.minorType"></a>
Hemiprocne minor [=Streptoprocne zonaris minor] <strong>Type locality</strong>
<ul>
<li>The type locality given by Lawrence is "Bogot&aacute;", however
this bird is described as coming from coastal Venezuela and Trinidad!"</li>
<li>Ken Parkes. 1994. <cite>"Taxonomic notes on the White-collared Swift (<i>Streptoprocne zonaris</i>>
Avocetta <b>17</b>:97</cite> discusses the issue of the type locality. Parkes says:<pre>
<i>Remarks:</i> Naumburg (1930) pointed out that
Lawrence's holotype of <i>minor</i> from "Bogot&aacute;" (which I 
[KC Parkes] have examined at the American Museum of 
Natural History) was not of the well-known "Bogot&aacute;" trade
skin make, but instead matches "the well-known
Orinoco or Trinidad make".  This was reiterated by 
Zimmer (1953) who pointed out its resemblance to
other Trinidad specimens. These clearly belong to the
subspecies of the coastal mountains of Venezuela; the
holotype differs only in having a flat wing 
measurement of of 180 mm, 3 mm shorter than any 
mainland specimen (its wing lenght is cited by
Zimmer and others as 178 mm, but he undoubtedly
did not flatten the wing fully on the ruler).  I have no 
hesitation in accepting Zimmer's tentative suggestion,
and restrict the type locality of <i>Hemiprocne minor</i>
Lawrence to Trinidad.  ffrench (1991) believed that the
swifts of this species seen in Trinidad represented "a
post-breeding dispersal, probably from the 
Venezuelan Andes." Birds from those mountains,
however, belong to a different subspecies than do the 
available Trinidad specimens; as the latter are
matched by those of the coastal mountains, the name
<i>minor</i> will apply to the coastal and not the Andean
birds.</pre></li>
<li>Of interest I [APP] am not aware of any discussion as to how Lawrence came to put
"Bogot&aacute" in his description of the type. I interpret it to simply be an error.</li>


</ul>
2004.05.18


