<hr><A name="M.fascinans">
<b>Microeca</b> Type controversy
<ul>
<li> Microeca fascinans (<a href="../bio/biol.html#Latham" target="ref_fr">Latham</a>) <a href="./n/l.html#Latham 1802" target="ref_fr"> 1802</a> <i><a href="../cit/jours.html#Suppl.ind.orn." target="ref_fr">Suppl.ind.orn.</a></i> p.xlvi
<ul>
<li> Peters (11:557,8 Mayr) gives the following:<ul>
<li> "Type by monotypy <i>Microeca assimilis</i> Gould". Peters 11:557.
<li> Type locality: "Swan River, Western Australia." Peters 11:558.
<li> <i>Microeca assimilis</i> Gould is a subspecies of <i>Micoreca leucophaea</i> = <i>Sylvia leucophaea</i> Latham, 1801.
<li> The listing for <i>M. leucophaea leucophaea</i> (Latham) has in synonomy <i>Microeca fascinans</i> auctorum (nec <i>Loxia fascinans</i> Latham).</ul>

<li> Sibley and Monroe p.445 have a note  citing the authority of McAllen & Bruce, and R. Schodde and indicating that <i>Loxia fascinans</i> Latham, 1801 is the name with priority and it is =<i>M. leucophaea</i> (Latham), 1801.</ul>
<li> Therefore, I interpret <i>M. assimilis</i> Gould = <i>Loxia fascinans</i> Latham as the type
<li> The type locality of the genus would be the type locality of <i>Loxia fascinans</i> which the Richmond index gives as Port Jackson, New South Wales.
</ul></ul></ul>

<hr><A name="M.tristis"><ul>
<li> Meiglyptes tristis (<a href="../bio/bioh.html#Horsfield" target="ref_fr">Horsfield</a>) 1821 <i><a href="../cit/jourt.html#Trans.Linn.Soc.London" target="ref_fr">Trans.Linn.Soc.London</a>(1) </i> 13 p.177
<ul>
<li> Type by monotypy <i>Picus poicilphus</i> Temminck = <i>Picus tristis</i> Horsfield.
<li> Type locality (Peters representation): "Java." Peters 6:148.
</ul></ul>

