<P><HR></P>
<P><A NAME="M.phasianella">Columba phasianella (<A HREF="../bio/biot.html#Temmick">Temmick</A> 1821 <A HREF="../cit/jourp.html#Pl.Col."><I>Pl.Col. Rend.</I></A> Livr.17 pl.100 </P>

<UL>
<LI>A complex, confusing, and controversial situation here. 
My understandings here result from the work of Steven Gregory, and Colin Jones; the final resolution
stems from the work of Dick Schodde.</LI>
<LI>The questions include: which is the type?, who designated it?, and where? </LI>
<LI>Gregory's notes indicate:</LI>

<UL>
<LI>"Peters (<b>3</b>:75) clearly states that the taxon subsequently designated is <I>Columba phasianella</I> Temminck, 1824, pl. col. 100. (not <I>Columba phasianella</I> Temminck 1821). The 'Temminck, 1824' is misleading, I suspect it actually refers to the text to livr. 17, issued on or before August 1822 (according to Dickinson)."</LI>
<LI>"G. R. Gray, 1840, lists two species: <I>M. amboinensis</I> (Lath.) and <I>C. phasianellus</I> Temm. Pl. Col. 100., however this '<I>amboinensis</I>' is not the 'Amboina' <I>Columba amboinensis</I> Linnaeus, 1766, but rather the 'composite' used by Latham, Lesson, and later by Gray and others. Only <I>C. phasianellus</I> (<I>sensu</I> Temminck, 1822) was originally included."</LI>
<LI>[Swainson Class. Birds 2, 1837 has not currently been seen by Gregory but he notes] "if the species depicted by Temminck on pl. 100 of the Pl. Col. is an included species [in Swainsons erection of <B>Macropygia</B>] as indicated by Salvadori, 1893, p.346 '(ex Pl. Col. 100)', then it can be a type candidate." </LI>
<LI>"Interestingly Peters (3: 75,79) goes on to suggest that this taxon actually = <I>M. tenuirostris</I> Bonaparte, 1854, and not the nominate <I>Columba phasianella</I> Temm., 1821, Trans. Linn. Soc. London, 13, pt1, p. 129. This is confirmed by Mathews (1927) and RAOU Check-list (1929)."</LI>
<LI>"As to the subsequent designation, it is either:</LI>

<UL>
<LI>G. R. Gray, 1840, p. 58. (listed by Mathews, with the '<I>amboinensis</I>' ignored) or </LI>
<LI>Salvadori, 1882, Orn. Pap. e Mol., 3, p.132. (listed by Peters, and unseen [Gregory]). </LI>
<LI>It is <B>not</B> Salvadori, 1893, Cat. Birds Brit. Mus., XXI, p.335., as the '<I>phasianella</I>' cited is not the Pl. Col. taxon." </LI></UL>
</UL>
<li>Subsequent input by Richard Schodde <pre>
The following points, I think, tell it all.<ol>

<li> "<i>M. phasianella</i>, Pl. Col. 100", name and reference, was the one of the 
included species in Swainson's original description of <b>Macropygia</b>, and was later 
designated its type species.  As no other included species has been so 
designated, all that remains is to clarify the identity of "<i>M. phasianella</i>, Pl. Col. 
100".</li>

<li> Whatever is said on wrappers and however much we like to interpret what 
was in people's minds, the root information bearing on the identity of "<i>M. 
phasianella</i>, Pl. Col. 100" is what was actually said <b>IN</b> the original reference 
itself.</li>

<li> I have now checked that reference, and, despite my halting French, it is 
clear that Temminck there simply expanded his concept of <i>Columba phasianella</i> 
as published in the Trans.Linn.Soc. in 1821 to include the populations through 
the Moluccas and Sundas to the Philippines (and "jusqu'a la Nouvelle 
Hollande"); even "<i>Columba Amboinensis</i> Lath." was included as the young of the year.</li>

<li> The Philippines are only specified according to the fruit eating habits of 
the species: The pigeon became common around Manilla in February where it 
could be shot in numbers.</li>

<li> The opening two sentences of the text to Pl. 100 - Adult read: "Nous 
figurons cet oiseau sous le plumage de l'etat parfait.  Une courte notice, pris sur 
un jeune individu tue a la Nouvelle-Hollande , a ete donnee dans le vol. 13 
des Transactions Linneennes, pag. 129, sous le noms indiques ci-dessus..."  
These names, given in the heading, are "Colombe Phasianelle" and 'Columba 
phasianella. Temm.'.</li>

<li> So "<i>M. phasianella</i>" in "Pl. Col. 100" is not a new name based on a 
Philippine or Sundan form.  It is the same name as <i>Columba phasianella</i> Temminck, 
1821, which should therefore be cited as the nominal type species of <b>Macropygia</b>
Swainson.</li>

<li>  As for a footnote in H&amp;M, why not refer to to the Zoo. Cat. Aust. 37.2, 
p. 23 for explanation.  It's not as clear as it could be, but it is enough.  If 
anyone isn't satisfied with that and wants to query, let them waste their 
time working it out.</li>
</ol>

All a salutary illustration of the need to check original sources.

Cheers, 

Dick</pre>
</UL>

APP:SG:APP:RS 2002.01.13; 2004.11.24

